## Testing philosophy
- Test observable behavior, not implementation trivia.
- Prefer table-driven tests when they improve clarity.
- Use subtests when they improve readability and failure isolation.
- Keep tests deterministic and easy to understand.

## Unit tests
- Keep mocks limited to true boundaries.
- Prefer real collaborators for simple internal logic.
- Use t.Helper for helpers.
- Use t.Cleanup for cleanup logic tied to the test lifecycle.

## Integration tests
- Cover important workflows and boundary contracts.
- Use realistic fixtures and explicit setup.
- Avoid hidden environmental assumptions.

## Fuzzing
- Add fuzz tests for parsers, decoders, protocol handlers, input normalization, and security-sensitive logic.
- Use fuzzing where untrusted or attacker-controlled input exists.
- Keep fuzz targets focused and reproducible.

## Benchmarks
- Benchmark hot paths, allocation-sensitive code, serialization, and concurrency-sensitive flows.
- Do not micro-optimize before measurement.

## Quality gates
- New behavior must come with tests or a clear reason why tests are not appropriate.
- Prefer go test, go test -race where relevant, go vet, and modern static analysis in CI.
- Keep tests fast enough for frequent execution.